					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Squ=
are matrix used to represent a graph or network</div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_theory" title=3D"Graph=
 theory">graph theory</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comp=
uter_science" title=3D"Computer science">computer science</a>, an <b>adjace=
ncy matrix</b> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_matrix"=
 title=3D"Square matrix">square matrix</a> used to represent a finite <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_(discrete_mathematics)" title=3D"=
Graph (discrete mathematics)">graph</a>. The elements of the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_(mathematics)" title=3D"Matrix (mathemati=
cs)">matrix</a> indicate whether pairs of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Vertex_(graph_theory)" title=3D"Vertex (graph theory)">vertices</a>=
 are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neighbourhood_(graph_theory)"=
 title=3D"Neighbourhood (graph theory)">adjacent</a> or not within the grap=
h.
</p><p>In the special case of a finite <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Simple_graph" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Simple graph">simple grap=
h</a>, the adjacency matrix is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/(=
0,1)-matrix" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"(0,1)-matrix">(0,1)-matrix</a> =
with zeros on its diagonal. If the graph is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Glossary_of_graph_theory_terms#undirected" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Glossary of graph theory terms">undirected</a> (i.e. all of its <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glossary_of_graph_theory_terms#edge"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Glossary of graph theory terms">edges</a> a=
re bidirectional), the adjacency matrix is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Symmetric_matrix" title=3D"Symmetric matrix">symmetric</a>.=20
The relationship between a graph and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Eigenvalue" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Eigenvalue">eigenvalues</=
a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvector" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Eigenvector">eigenvectors</a> of its adjacency matrix is s=
tudied in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spectral_graph_theory" t=
itle=3D"Spectral graph theory">spectral graph theory</a>.
</p><p>The adjacency matrix of a graph should be distinguished from its <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Incidence_matrix" title=3D"Incidence =
matrix">incidence matrix</a>, a different matrix representation whose eleme=
nts indicate whether vertex=E2=80=93edge pairs are <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Incidence_(graph)" title=3D"Incidence (graph)">incident</a=
> or not, and its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Degree_matrix" t=
itle=3D"Degree matrix">degree matrix</a>, which contains information about =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Degree_(graph_theory)" title=
=3D"Degree (graph theory)">degree</a> of each vertex.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definition">Definition</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAdjacency_matrix=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Definition"><spa=
n>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></di=
v>
<p>For a simple graph with vertex set <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>U</i> =3D =
{<i>u</i><sub>1</sub>, ..., <i>u</i><sub><i>n</i></sub>}</span>, the adjace=
ncy matrix is a square <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =C3=97 <i>n</i></sp=
an> matrix <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</spa=
n> such that its element <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">A<sub>ij</sub></span> is 1 when there is an edge from vertex <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><i>u</i><sub>i</sub></span> to vertex <span class=3D"texh=
tml"><i>u</i><sub>j</sub></span>, and 0 when there is no edge.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adja=
cency_matrix#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The diagonal elements of the matrix ar=
e all 0, since edges from a vertex to itself (<a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Loop_(graph_theory)" title=3D"Loop (graph theory)">loops</a>) a=
re not allowed in simple graphs. It is also sometimes useful in <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_graph_theory" title=3D"Algebraic gr=
aph theory">algebraic graph theory</a> to replace the nonzero elements with=
 algebraic variables.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adjacency_matrix#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The =
same concept can be extended to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mu=
ltigraph" title=3D"Multigraph">multigraphs</a> and graphs with loops by sto=
ring the number of edges between each two vertices in the corresponding mat=
rix element, and by allowing nonzero diagonal elements. Loops may be counte=
d either once (as a single edge) or twice (as two vertex-edge incidences), =
as long as a consistent convention is followed. Undirected graphs often use=
 the latter convention of counting loops twice, whereas directed graphs typ=
ically use the former convention.
</p>
