<span class=3D"texhtml">0<sub><i>r</i>,<i>r</i></sub></span> and <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml">0<sub><i>s</i>,<i>s</i></sub></span> represent the <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i> =C3=97 <i>r</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>s</i> =C3=97 <i>s</i></span> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zer=
o_matrix" title=3D"Zero matrix">zero matrices</a>. In this case, the smalle=
r matrix <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">B</span>=
 uniquely represents the graph, and the remaining parts of <span class=3D"t=
exhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> can be discarded as redu=
ndant. <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">B</span> i=
s sometimes called the <i>biadjacency matrix</i>.
</p><p>Formally, let <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>G</i> =3D (<i>U</i>, <i>V</=
i>, <i>E</i>)</span> be a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bipartit=
