ss=3D"texhtml"><i>U</i> =3D {<i>u</i><sub>1</sub>, ..., <i>u</i><sub><i>r</=
i></sub>}</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>V</i> =3D {<i>v</i><sub>1</sub=
>, ..., <i>v</i><sub><i>s</i></sub>}</span> and edges <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">E</span>. The biadjacency matrix is th=
e <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i> =C3=97 <i>s</i></span> 0=E2=80=931 matri=
x <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">B</span> in whi=
ch <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i><sub><i>i</i>,<i>j</i></sub> =3D 1</span=
> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/If_and_only_if" title=3D"If and =
only if">if and only if</a> <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>u</i><sub><i>i</i><=
/sub>, <i>v</i><sub><i>j</i></sub>) =E2=88=88 <i>E</i></span>.
</p><p>If <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">G</span=
> is a bipartite <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multigraph" title=
=3D"Multigraph">multigraph</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Weighted_graph" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Weighted graph">weighted gra=
ph</a>, then the elements <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:=
italic;">b<i><sub>i,j</sub></i></span> are taken to be the number of edges =
between the vertices or the weight of the edge <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>=
u</i><sub><i>i</i></sub>, <i>v</i><sub><i>j</i></sub>)</span>, respectively=
.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Variations">Variations</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAdjacency_matrix=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Variations"><spa=
n>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></di=
v>
<p>An <span class=3D"nowrap"><span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>a</i>, <i>b</i>, <=
i>c</i>)</span></span>-adjacency matrix <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> of a simple graph has <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><i>A</i><sub><i>i</i>,<i>j</i></sub> =3D <i>a</i></span> if <span class=
=3D"texhtml">(<i>i</i>, <i>j</i>)</span> is an edge, <span class=3D"texhtml=
 mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> if it is not, and <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span> on the diagonal. Th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seidel_adjacency_matrix" title=
=3D"Seidel adjacency matrix">Seidel adjacency matrix</a> is a <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"nowrap">(=E2=88=921, 1, 0)</span></span>-adjace=
ncy matrix. This matrix is used in studying <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Strongly_regular_graph" title=3D"Strongly regular graph">strongly=
 regular graphs</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Two-graph"=
 title=3D"Two-graph">two-graphs</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adjacency_matrix#cite_note-3">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p><p>The <b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Distance_matrix" tit=
le=3D"Distance matrix">distance matrix</a></b> has in position <span class=
=3D"texhtml">(<i>i</i>, <i>j</i>)</span> the distance between vertices <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">v<sub>i</sub></span> =
and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">v<sub>j</sub>=
</span>. The distance is the length of a shortest path connecting the verti=
ces. Unless lengths of edges are explicitly provided, the length of a path =
is the number of edges in it. The distance matrix resembles a high power of=
 the adjacency matrix, but instead of telling only whether or not two verti=
ces are connected (i.e., the connection matrix, which contains <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra" title=3D"Boolean algebra">Boo=
lean values</a>), it gives the exact distance between them.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Examples">Examples</h2><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAdjacency_matrix&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Examples"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Undirected_graphs">Undirect=
ed graphs</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAd=
jacency_matrix&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Un=
directed graphs"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket=
">]</span></span></div>
<p>The convention followed here (for undirected graphs) is that each edge a=
dds 1 to the appropriate cell in the matrix, and each loop (an edge from a =
vertex to itself) adds 2 to the appropriate cell on the diagonal in the mat=
rix.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Adjacency_matrix#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This allows the degre=
e of a vertex to be easily found by taking the sum of the values in either =
its respective row or column in the adjacency matrix.
</p>
