<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Directed_graphs">Directed g=
raphs</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAdjace=
ncy_matrix&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Direct=
ed graphs"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<p>The adjacency matrix of a directed graph can be asymmetric. One can defi=
ne the adjacency matrix of a directed graph either such that=20
</p>
<ol><li>a non-zero element <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">A<sub>ij</sub></span> indicates an edge from <span class=3D"texht=
ml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">i</span> to <span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">j</span> or</li>
<li>it indicates an edge from <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-st=
yle:italic;">j</span> to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">i</span>.</li></ol>
<p>The former definition is commonly used in graph theory and social networ=
k analysis (e.g., sociology, political science, economics, psychology).<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Adjacency_matrix#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The latter is more common in =
other applied sciences (e.g., dynamical systems, physics, network science) =
where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> is=
 sometimes used to describe linear dynamics on graphs.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adjacency_ma=
trix#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Using the first definition, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Directed_graph#Indegree_and_outdegree" title=3D"Directed graph">in-deg=
rees</a> of a vertex can be computed by summing the entries of the correspo=
