<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Isomorphism_and_invariants"=
>Isomorphism and invariants</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DAdjacency_matrix&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=
=3D"Edit section: Isomorphism and invariants"><span>edit</span></a><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Suppose two directed or undirected graphs <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>G</=
i><sub>1</sub></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>G</i><sub>2</sub></spa=
n> with adjacency matrices <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i><sub>1</sub></sp=
an> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i><sub>2</sub></span> are given. <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><i>G</i><sub>1</sub></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><i>G</i><sub>2</sub></span> are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G=
raph_isomorphism" title=3D"Graph isomorphism">isomorphic</a> if and only if=
 there exists a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Permutation_matrix=
" title=3D"Permutation matrix">permutation matrix</a> <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">P</span> such that
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e PA_{1}P^{-1}=3DA_{2}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>P</mi>
        <msub>
          <mi>A</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>1</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <msup>
          <mi>P</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
            <mn>1</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>A</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle PA_{1}P^{-1}=
=3DA_{2}.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/6b51b8853d371bc9ef909bf3f2adcfdb20e3acc9" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:15.24ex; height:3.009ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle PA_=
{1}P^{-1}=3DA_{2}.}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>In particular, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i><sub>1</sub></span> and <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i><sub>2</sub></span> are <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Similar_(linear_algebra)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Similar (linear algebra)">similar</a> and therefore have the same <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minimal_polynomial_(linear_algebra)" ti=
tle=3D"Minimal polynomial (linear algebra)">minimal polynomial</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Characteristic_polynomial" title=3D"Chara=
cteristic polynomial">characteristic polynomial</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Eigenvalues"=
>eigenvalues</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant" tit=
le=3D"Determinant">determinant</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Trace_(matrix)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Trace (matrix)">trace</=
a>. These can therefore serve as isomorphism invariants of graphs. However,=
 two graphs may possess the same set of eigenvalues but not be isomorphic.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Adjacency_matrix#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Such <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_operator" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Linear =
operator">linear operators</a> are said to be <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Isospectral" title=3D"Isospectral">isospectral</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Matrix_powers">Matrix power=
s</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAdjacency_=
matrix&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Matrix po=
wers"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span><=
/span></div>
<p>If <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> is=
 the adjacency matrix of the directed or undirected graph <span class=3D"te=
xhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">G</span>, then the matrix <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i><sup><i>n</i></sup></span> (i.e., the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_multiplication" title=3D"Matrix multipli=
cation">matrix product</a> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-st=
yle:italic;">n</span> copies of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-=
style:italic;">A</span>) has an interesting interpretation: the element <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"nowrap">(<i>i</i>, <i>j</i>)</span></sp=
an> gives the number of (directed or undirected) <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Path_(graph_theory)" title=3D"Path (graph theory)">walks</a>=
 of length <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</spa=
n> from vertex <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">i<=
/span> to vertex <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
j</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Adjacency_matrix#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> If <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> is the smallest no=
nnegative integer, such that for some <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">i</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-s=
tyle:italic;">j</span>, the element <span class=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"=
nowrap">(<i>i</i>, <i>j</i>)</span></span> of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>A<=
/i><sup><i>n</i></sup></span> is positive, then <span class=3D"texhtml mvar=
" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> is the distance between vertex <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">i</span> and vertex <=
span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">j</span>. A great =
example of how this is useful is in counting the number of triangles in an =
undirected graph <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
G</span>, which is exactly the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tra=
ce_(linear_algebra)" title=3D"Trace (linear algebra)">trace</a> of <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i><sup>3</sup></span> divided by 3 or 6 depending on =
whether the graph is directed or not. We divide by those values to compensa=
te for the overcounting of each triangle. In an undirected graph, each tria=
ngle will be counted twice for all three nodes, because the path can be fol=
lowed clockwise or counterclockwise&nbsp;: ijk or ikj. The adjacency matrix=
 can be used to determine whether or not the graph is <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Connectivity_(graph_theory)" title=3D"Connectivity (gra=
ph theory)">connected</a>.
</p><p>If a directed graph has a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/N=
ilpotent_matrix" title=3D"Nilpotent matrix">nilpotent</a> adjacency matrix =
(i.e., if there exists <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ita=
lic;">n</span> such that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i><sup><i>n</i></sup=
></span> is the zero matrix), then it is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Directed_acyclic_graph" title=3D"Directed acyclic graph">directed =
acyclic graph</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adjacency_matrix#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Data_structures">Data struc=
tures</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAdjace=
ncy_matrix&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Data =
structures"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<p>The adjacency matrix may be used as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Data_structure" title=3D"Data structure">data structure</a> for the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_(abstract_data_type)" title=
=3D"Graph (abstract data type)">representation of graphs</a> in computer pr=
ograms for manipulating graphs. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bo=
olean_data_type" title=3D"Boolean data type">Boolean data types</a> are use=
d, such as <code>True</code> and <code>False</code> in <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)" title=3D"Python (progra=
mming language)">Python</a>. The main alternative data structure, also in u=
se for this application, is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ad=
jacency_list" title=3D"Adjacency list">adjacency list</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adjacen=
cy_matrix#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-clrs_13-0" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adjacency_matrix#cite_=
note-clrs-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The space needed to represent an adjacency matrix and the time neede=
d to perform operations on them is dependent on the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_representation" title=3D"Matrix representation">ma=
trix representation</a> chosen for the underlying matrix. <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sparse_matrix_representation" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Sparse matrix representation">Sparse matrix representations</a> o=
nly store non-zero matrix entries and implicitly represent the zero entries=
. They can, for example, be used to represent <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Sparse_graph" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sparse graph">spar=
se graphs</a> without incurring the space overhead from storing the many ze=
ro entries in the adjacency matrix of the sparse graph. In the following se=
ction the adjacency matrix is assumed to be represented by an <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Array_data_structure" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Array data structure">array data structure</a> so that zero and non-z=
ero entries are all directly represented in storage.
</p><p>Because each entry in the adjacency matrix requires only one bit, it=
 can be represented in a very compact way, occupying only <span class=3D"te=
xhtml">|<i>V</i><span style=3D"white-space: nowrap;">=E2=80=89</span>|<sup>=
2</sup>=E2=80=8A/=E2=80=8A8</span> bytes to represent a directed graph, or =
(by using a packed triangular format and only storing the lower triangular =
part of the matrix) approximately <span class=3D"texhtml">|<i>V</i><span st=
yle=3D"white-space: nowrap;">=E2=80=89</span>|<sup>2</sup>=E2=80=8A/=E2=80=
=8A16</span> bytes to represent an undirected graph. Although slightly more=
 succinct representations are possible, this method gets close to the infor=
mation-theoretic lower bound for the minimum number of bits needed to repre=
sent all <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>=
-vertex graphs.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adjacency_matrix#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For sto=
ring graphs in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Text_file" title=3D=
"Text file">text files</a>, fewer bits per byte can be used to ensure that =
all bytes are text characters, for instance by using a <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Base64" title=3D"Base64">Base64</a> representation.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Adjacency_matrix#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Besides avoiding wasted s=
pace, this compactness encourages <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Locality_of_reference" title=3D"Locality of reference">locality of referenc=
e</a>.
However, for a large <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sparse_graph"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sparse graph">sparse graph</a>, adjacency l=
ists require less storage space, because they do not waste any space repres=
enting edges that are <i>not</i> present.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-clrs_13-1" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adjacency_matrix#=
cite_note-clrs-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-gt_16-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adjacency_matrix#cite_note-gt-=
16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p><p>An alternative form of adjacency matrix (which, however, requires a =
larger amount of space) replaces the numbers in each element of the matrix =
with pointers to edge objects (when edges are present) or null pointers (wh=
en there is no edge).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-gt_16-1" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adjacency_matrix#cite_note-gt-16"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> It is also possible to store <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Weighted_graph" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Weighted graph">edge weigh=
ts</a> directly in the elements of an adjacency matrix.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
clrs_13-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adj=
acency_matrix#cite_note-clrs-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Besides the space tradeoff, the different data structures also facil=
itate different operations. Finding all vertices adjacent to a given vertex=
 in an adjacency list is as simple as reading the list, and takes time prop=
ortional to the number of neighbors. With an adjacency matrix, an entire ro=
w must instead be scanned, which takes a larger amount of time, proportiona=
l to the number of vertices in the whole graph. On the other hand, testing =
whether there is an edge between two given vertices can be determined at on=
